<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-187-038  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 187 038.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  March 1990 v7 n3 p93(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Take this data and store it.(data storage options)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baldwin, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Every computer user faces the dilemma of what to do with data whenits not in use.andP;  The choice of a final solution is more a matterof the application a user employs most frequently, rather than aresult of the advertising hype that surrounds products.andP;  Opticalmedia is the current darling of the industry, but its mainstrength is in the recording and high-capacity storage of images.andO;Tape technology dominates the world of data acquisition.andP;  Diskstorage surpasses both of these in terms of speed and conveniencebecause it is on-line.andP;  Digital audio technology (DAT) is growingrapidly.andP;  Other developments influencing selections include diskcapacity, which is increasing even as the physical size of disksgets smaller, and a 3M Corp development called 'long tape', thatis half the thickness of standard tape, allowing 1,000 feet in acartridge instead of 500.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Storage MediaDisk StorageTape StorageErasable Optical Memory.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>